node.text:
This morning, I had the honor of speaking at the Downtown Mobile Alliance Mayor’s Breakfast about some of the plans we have in the works for the downtown area.

From the restoration of Bienville Square to the recently announced plans to activate the riverfront, Broad Street revitalization, Roll Mobile, and Artwalk to CPSI moving their headquarters to Conception - Downtown is thriving.

node.text:
Calagaz Printing, a Mobile print shop, has switched from printing menus to manufacturing face shields for health care workers.

With business down because of #COVID19, one of their team members came up with this wild idea, to produce face shields. Turns out they can not only do it, but they can produce a bunch, quickly!

So, in less than a week, they created a prototype, met with hospitals, ordered materials and today they will deliver the first 5,000 to Mobile’s four hospitals. Next week they plan to ramp up and produce 5,000/day. 
Kudos to Calagaz for thinking outside the box and working hard to make this happen. As a local, family-owned business, they are helping us turn the tide in the fight against Coronavirus and keeping their employees working, too.

City operations will close with the exception of emergency personnel in response to Hurricane Ida. The City of Mobile will designate the Alert status mobilization period for Hurricane Ida as of 12:00 pm Sunday, August 29, 2021, until a time to be determined.  In accordance with this order, City of Mobile offices will be closed Monday, August 30th. During this time period, employees will be paid in accordance with the City of Mobile’s Emergency or Disaster Days Policy. We will continue to monitor the status of the storm and notify employees of any changes.

William S. Stimpson
Mayor

node.text:
I’m happy to share that the National Fish and Wildlife Foundation (NFWF) has announced an amendment to a Gulf Environmental Benefit Fund (GEBF) project that will help secure and protect sensitive wetlands along Mobile’s waterfront. This $2 million award from NFWF will allow the City of Mobile to finalize the purchase of 45 acres of wetland habitat adjacent to the recently acquired “Brookley by the Bay” property that we announced last December.

These wetlands represent one of the largest intact segments of bayfront wetlands in the City of Mobile — a critical piece of our waterfront ecosystem. Once acquired, these wetlands will be managed in a way that protects and enhances their ecological function. Through a conservation easement with the South Alabama Land Trust, the City of Mobile will be able to ensure this land is protected in perpetuity
This is only a small portion of the nearly 300 acres at Brookley the City of Mobile has acquired or will acquire from the University of South Alabama Foundation. We are already working to turn 150 acres of this property into a public park so that it can be accessed by all Mobilians.

node.text:
Want to hear some good news this evening? Last month, the Alabama tourism Department named the Exploreum Science Center the 2021 Alabama Tourism Attraction of the Year. This is a testament to the great work the Exploreum’s staff and leadership are doing to bring quality exhibits and attractions to the City of Mobile. In fact, since the inception of the Alabama Tourism Attraction of the Year award, the Exploreum is the only organization to have the honor of receiving it twice.

I recently had a chance to visit the Exploreum to see the “Cosmos 2021: Adventure into the Unknown” exhibit. This exhibit is the result of a unique collaboration with NASA that takes visitors on a journey through the past, present and future of humanity’s journey into the unknowns of space. It will be closing on September 6, so you should come see it while you can. If you’d like more information about the exhibit or details about tickets, you can visit the Exploreum’s website: https://www.exploreum.com/exhibits/special/

node.text:
I was thrilled to join Gov. Kay Ivey and other state and local officials on a tour of the new AltaPointe Behavioral Health Crisis Center in Mobile. This state-of-the-art facility will make 24-hour care available to those experiencing mental health crises. This facility has been a welcome addition to our community since it opened in May, and it will be an invaluable asset for families, law enforcement officers and individuals dealing with someone suffering from a mental health crisis.

I’d like to thank Gov. Ivey for her leadership and the state legislature for securing the funding for the crisis center in Mobile and three others across the state. The addition of this facility will help alleviate the pressure on local jails, hospitals and police officers that routinely respond to calls related to individuals experiencing a mental health crisis. This will also help our citizens receive the right care at the right time

node.text:
It’s not every day you get to celebrate a 231st birthday, but that’s what the City of Mobile did today in recognition of the United States Coast Guard’s centuries of service on the Gulf and around the world. Since 1790, USCG has kept the nation’s waterways safe, and Sector Mobile serves a massive area that spans four states, five deep-water ports and 1,700 nautical miles of inland, river and coastal waterways. 

The Guardsmen at Sector Mobile routinely support search and rescue missions as well as law enforcement and homeland security operations — enforcing all federal laws in the maritime domain, protecting living marine resources, and responding to reports of marine pollution. They protect our citizens and waterways everyday and it was a pleasure to have Guardsmen from Sector Mobile help us recognize August 4, 2021, as Coast Guard Day in the City of Mobile, Alabama.

node.text:
Yesterday, I joined the Mobile City Council in recognizing our community’s continued efforts to meet the standards set in the Americans with Disabilities Act signed into law 31 years ago today. We were joined during the council meeting by representatives from the Independent Living Center of Mobile and Business Accessibility for All to help mark the anniversary of this landmark legislation that has done so much to reduce barriers for the 54 million Americans living with disabilities every day.

We recognize this day each year to celebrate the progress that has been made in the City of Mobile, to reaffirm the principles of equality and inclusion and to show that our City remains committed to fully implementing the ADA in public spaces, businesses and throughout the community at large.

Yesterday, the leaders from our Neighborhood Development Department and I helped welcome a group of fantastic young people from all across the Southeast who’ve come to help paint and repair homes in the Africatown community. 

They wound up here through the City of Mobile’s “Volunteer Painting Program,” which uses federal funding to cover the hard cost of repairs and improvements to homes in underserved communities. This year’s volunteer participants are being coordinated through the Atlanta-based non-profit, Mission Serve.

node.text: On Monday, I joined WAVE Transit System General Manager Damon Dash to demonstrate some of the features on the new busses we’ll soon be adding to our fleet. These vehicles are built specifically for public transportation in an urban setting and that goes well beyond the improved looks. They are designed from the ground up to better serve all passengers — including those with limited mobility or who require the use of a walker or wheelchair. We’re on schedule to have four of these on the road by the end of July.

This morning, I joined staff from Mobile Bay National Estuary Program and members of their construction and consultant team to view the progress of their restoration project to stabilize 1800 feet of 12 Mile Creek headwaters. The headwaters project and our partnership with MBNEP will complement the City of Mobile’s 12 Mile Creek stabilization project, which stretches from East Drive to Langan Lake, in the efforts to reduce the energy of stormwater and sediment loads traveling down 12 Mile Creek to Langan Lake. We also talked about ongoing invasive species abatement in Langan Lake, which will continue through the City’s Langan Lake Dredging project.
